<p>Trying to ding me for not being open to discussing things with people who are not like me while simultaneously citing my anger as an excuse for you to avoid talking with me because that&#8217;s not how you prefer to discuss things is one level of hypocrisy. But trying to ding me for that while also <a href="#comment-169020" rel="nofollow">citing my anger as an excuse to avoid &#8220;having personal information about [you] used&#8221;</a> <em>and</em> for not considering personal information about you as part of your arguments? That&#8217;s exactly the kind of mind-bending hypocrisy this post references!</p>
<p>If you can&#8217;t see that, then, for my own sake, I&#8217;ll just rescind the invitation to discuss personal experiences with you in the first place.</p>
<p>So if you do come back, I&#8217;d be pleased to see you do it with a face and a real name and some &#8220;accomplishments&#8221; of your own. Until you do, you&#8217;re just <a href="http://maybemaimed.com/2010/02/24/open-thread-when-educators-are-censors/" rel="nofollow">another piece of stop energy</a> on whom I&#8217;ve already wasted more time than I arguably should have.</p>
