   	<li class="clear" id="comment-169678">
    	<div class="comment even thread-even depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://notjustbitchy.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Stabbity</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>18 Jun 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-169678">22:01</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/a37da6663cc58efd506d56dc245fc45f?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>Whenever I hear someone tell an activist they&#8217;re too angry, I bristle. I&#8217;ve heard that a lot on feminist blogs, and I have yet to see it actually mean &#8216;I&#8217;m concerned that your attitude may push your potential allies away. What I have heard it mean is &#8216;your anger makes me uncomfortable&#8217;, and &#8216;my comfort level is more important than your frustration about being treated badly&#8217;.</p>
<p>Also, angry activists are important. I read a really interesting article which I wish I could credit for this idea, but I don&#8217;t remember enough of the details to find it again. The author&#8217;s argument was that loud, angry activists are great at raising awareness of issues because they&#8217;re loud, angry, and hard to ignore. Once people are aware of the issue, they start paying attention to the more moderate activists too. Then angry activists serve another purpose by making the moderate activist&#8217;s demands look relatively minor compared to the sweeping changes more extreme activists want. Once people start thinking &#8216;okay, that guy&#8217;s a little out there, but that other guy isn&#8217;t really asking for so much&#8217;, it&#8217;s easier to get the things that &#8216;that other guy&#8217; is asking for.</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   	<li class="clear" id="comment-169695">
